Prosper Loan Data¶

by Chris Arnell¶

Prosper is an online loan company based in San Francisco. They do not have a brick and mortar store like most banks, and this means Prosper has a much lower cost of business than a normal bank. The data supplied contains information for Loans granted between 2009 & 2014

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Prosper Loans Data contains 113937 entries for loans given by Prosper after July 2009. Each entry has 81 variables, this seemed rather excessive so using the variable dictionary supplied by Udacity I highlighted variables that were of interest to me...

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features I am going to concentrate my exploration around are:

  • ListingCreationDate, Term, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, EstimatedEffectiveYield, EstimatedLoss, EstimatedReturn, ProsperScore, CreditScoreRangeLower0, CreditScoreRangeUpper, Occupation, StatedMonthlyIncome & LoanOriginalAmount'

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I will focus are the Borrower rate, Eastimated return, Year, Credit Score and also the Prosper Score

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this section I will clean the data, removing any unnecessary data for my exploration to mate the dataset far easier to work with.

Data Wrangling Findings


    1) There are a large number of columns with data that is unnecessary for my exploration

    2) The Dataset has a lot of missing values

    3) Credit Score Variable spread across 2 columns

    4) Loan date is displayed as a timestamp

3) Credit Score variable spread across 2 columns¶

Define¶

Add a column that displays an average of the upper & lower credit score, then drop the 2 columns Upper & Lower¶

Code¶

In [12]:
# Mathematic equation to find average of the 2 credit score columns and create a new column with these values 
df1['average_credit_score'] = (df1['CreditScoreRangeLower'] + df1['CreditScoreRangeUpper'])/2

# Drop the original credit score columns as we now have a new average credit score column
df1 = df1.drop('CreditScoreRangeLower', axis = 1)
df1 = df1.drop('CreditScoreRangeUpper', axis = 1)

plt.colorbar()

# Titles

plt.xlabel('Borrower Rate')
plt.ylabel('Prosper Score');

From looking at the comparison of Prosper Score v Borrower Rate it shows a clear negative correlation between the 2, as the Prosper Score increases, the Borrower Rate decreases. This makes sense as someone with a higher Proper Score (better) would expect to recieve a lower Borrower Rate.

From looking at the grids above displaying Loan Amount v Prosper Score for each year given in the dataset you can see a clear progression from 2009 where Prosper Score showed now relationship with the Loan Amount to 2014 where there is a clear positive correlation between Prosper Score.
